Now we create functions to standardise and normalise our data for PCA and NMF.

In [3]:
# standardise data for PCA 
def standardise(X):
    mu = np.mean(X, axis=0)
    std = np.std(X, axis=0)
    std_filled = std.copy()
    std_filled[std==0] = 1.
    Xbar = ((X-mu)/std_filled)
    return Xbar, mu, std

# normalise each element to a value between 0 and 1 for NMF
def normalise_nmf(X):
    return (X-np.min(X))/(np.max(X)-np.min(X))

Now we can prepare our data by dividing them by 255 to avoid overflow error, creating batches for the MLP and normalising and standardising for dimensionality reduction.

1.1 Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) (25 marks)¶

1.1.1¶

We will implement a multi-layer pereceptron (MLP) with an input layer of 784 (28 x 28) units, 3 hidden layers (with 200 neurons each) followed by an output layer with 10 neurons. In between our layers we will use the $\mathbf{\text{softplus}}$ activation function with $\beta=1$ and the $\mathbf{\text{softmax}}$ function as our activation function on our output layer. We will use $\mathbf{\text{stochastic gradient descent (SGD)}}$ as our optimisation method and adopt the $\mathbf{\text{KL divergence}}$ as our loss function. After building our model we will train our model on the training set in batches of 128 data points for 40 epochs varying our learning rate between $10^{-5}$ to $10^{-1}$.

Our model will be used to classify input images representing digits from 0 to 9 and output a digit from 0 to 9 with the highest probability of being the correct digit.

Before we start we will create a function to one-hot encode our target variables as we wish to transform our categorical variable to numerical.

In [5]:
def one_hot(y, num_classes=10):
    """
    Converts a vector of labels to a one-hot encoded matrix

    Args:
        y: vector of labels
        num_classes: number of classes
    
    Returns:
        one-hot encoded matrix
    """
    return np.eye(num_classes)[y]

Now let us define dense which implements the affine transfomation of our dense layers given weight and bias parameters, returning the pre-activation layer.

In [6]:
def dense(X, W, b):
    return b + X @ W.T

Now we can define our softplus activation function for our hidden layers. Using softplus as our activation function ensures our outputs are always positive but is also monotonic and differentiable, a benefit when using gradient-based optimisation. The softplus function is defined as,

$$ \text{softplus}(x) = \frac{\log \left( 1 + e^{\beta x } \right)}{\beta}. $$

In our model we will use $\beta = 1$.

In [7]:
def softplus(X, beta=1):
    return np.log(1 + np.exp(beta * X)) / beta

Next we will define our softmax function for our output layer. The softmax function serves a way to produce a probability distribution for classifying our images and since it is differentiable it enables us to use stochastic gradient descent. The softmax function is defined as,

$$ \text{softamx}(\mathbf{X})_i = \frac{e^{x_i}}{\sum_{j=1}^{n} e^{x_j}}. $$
In [8]:
def softmax(X):
    return np.exp(X) / np.sum(np.exp(X), axis=1, keepdims=True)

Our model will require weight and biases parameters these will have the following structure:

Input layer -> first hidden layer:

  • Kernel $\boldsymbol{W}^{(0)} \in\mathbb{R}^{784\times 200}$
  • Bias $\boldsymbol{b}^{(0)} \in\mathbb{R}^{200}$

Hidden layer -> hidden layer:

  • Kernel $\boldsymbol{W}^{(k)} \in\mathbb{R}^{200\times 200}$, $k=1, 2$
  • Bias $\boldsymbol{b}^{(k)} \in\mathbb{R}^{200}$, $k=1, 2$

Hidden layer -> output layer:

  • Kernel $\boldsymbol{W}^{(3)} \in\mathbb{R}^{200\times 10}$
  • Bias $\boldsymbol{b}^{(3)} \in\mathbb{R}^{10}$

We will initiliase our parameters using Glorot Initialisation where we initialise the kernel with samples from a zero-mean Gaussian distribution with variance $2 / (n_{in} + n_{out})$, where $n_{in}$ and $n_{out}$ are the number of neurons going in and out of the dense layer respectively and we initialise the bias parameters to 0.

In [9]:
def glorotInitalise(num_input, hidden_neurons, num_output):
    
    var0 = 2/(hidden_neurons + num_input)
    W0 = np.random.randn(hidden_neurons, num_input) * np.sqrt(var0)
    b0 = np.zeros(hidden_neurons)

    var1 = 2/(hidden_neurons + hidden_neurons)
    W1 = np.random.randn(hidden_neurons, hidden_neurons) * np.sqrt(var1)
    b1 = np.zeros(hidden_neurons)

    var2 = 2/(hidden_neurons + hidden_neurons)
    W2 = np.random.randn(hidden_neurons, hidden_neurons) * np.sqrt(var2)
    b2 = np.zeros(hidden_neurons)

    var3 = 2/(num_output + hidden_neurons)
    W3 = np.random.randn(num_output, hidden_neurons) * np.sqrt(var3)
    b3 = np.zeros(num_output)

    return W0, b0, W1, b1, W2, b2, W3, b3

Now we can create our MLP model using dense and our parameters and mlp will return our predictions.

In [10]:
def mlp(X, W0, b0, W1, b1, W2, b2, W3, b3):

    h = dense(X, W0, b0)
    h = softplus(h)
    h = dense(h, W1, b1)
    h = softplus(h)
    h = dense(h, W2, b2)
    h = softplus(h)
    h = dense(h, W3, b3)
    h = softmax(h)
    
    return h

Now that we have create our forward propagation segment of our MLP we now focus on the backpropagation portion of our model. Let us first implement our loss function, the KL divergence. The KL divergence is defined as

$$ L(y_{\text{true}}, y_{\text{pred}}) = y_{\text{true}} \cdot \log \left( \frac{y_{\text{true}}}{y_{\text{pred}}} \right) $$

We will use an pointwise implemenetation modified for one-hot encoding. Due to one-hot encoding we will have a 0 within $\log$ except for 1 case therefore our loss will read as $\log\left(1/y_{\text{pred}}\right)$.

In [11]:
def kl_loss(y_true, y_pred):
    """
    Computes the KL divergence loss between two distributions

    Args:
        y_true: true distribution
        y_pred: predicted distribution

    Returns:
        KL divergence loss
    """
    
    # np.where returns the index of the element with value 1 in our one-hot encoded target variable
    idx = np.where(y_true == 1)
    return -np.log(y_pred[idx])

Backpropagation is an algorithm in supervised learning that uses gradient descent to train an MLP, it works by calculating the gradient of the error with respect to the weights, upating our parameters accordingly. We can summarise the backpropagation algorithm as follows:

  1. Define our error for layer $k$ as $\delta^{(k)} _p = \frac{\partial L_i}{\partial a^{(k)}_p}$ where $i$ denotes the data point and the $p$-th activation in layer $k$
  2. Then propagate our input vector $x_i$ forward through our network computing all pre and post-activations using $a^{(k)} = (h^{(k-1)})^{T} W^{(k-1)} + b^{(k-1)}$
  3. Then evaluate $\delta^{(4)} = \frac{\partial L_i}{\partial a^{(4)}}$ for the output neuron
  4. Backpropagate errors to compute $\delta^{(k)}$ for each hidden unit using $\delta^{(k)} = \sigma^{'}(a^{(k)}) W^{(k)} \delta^{(k+1)}$
  5. Then we can obtain derivatives of $L_i$ with respect to weights and biases using $\frac{\partial L_i}{\partial w^{(k)} _{pq}} = \delta^{(k+1)} _p h^{(k)} _q$ and $\frac{\partial L_i}{\partial b^{(k)} _p} = \delta^{(k+1)} _p$

To implement backpropagation we first need to derive our output error,

$$ \delta^{(4)} = \frac{\partial L_i}{\partial a^{(4)}} = y_{\text{pred}} - y_{\text{true}}. $$
In [12]:
def output_error(y_true, y_pred):
    return y_pred - y_true

Next we will need to calculate the derivative of our softplus function.

$$ \frac{d (\text{softplus(x))}}{dx} = \frac{d}{dx}\log \left( 1 + e^{x } \right) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-x}}. $$
In [13]:
def activation_derivative(X):
    return 1/(1 + np.exp(-X))

Given the output error $\delta^{(4)}$ we can create a function to backpropagate $\delta^{(4)}$ to obtain $\delta^{(3)}, \ \delta^{(2)} \ \text{and} \ \delta^{(1)}$ using our weight matrices and pre-activations.

In [14]:
def backpropagate(delta, W, a):
    """
    Backpropagates our output error to obtain previous errors
    
    Args:
        delta: array of output error
        W: array of weights
        a: array of hidden layer pre-activations
        
    Returns:
        array hidden layer errors
    """
    return activation_derivative(a) * (delta @ W)

Finally given our errors and post-activations we can compute our gradient, derivative of $L_i$ with respect to our weights and biases. We can create a function grads which calculates the gradients averaged over the batch size.

In [15]:
def grads(delta1, delta2, delta3, delta4, h0, h1, h2, h3):
    """
    Compute gradients of loss averaged over batchsize
    
    Args:
        delta1: array of hidden layer error
        delta2: array of hidden layer error
        delta3: array of hidden layer error
        delta4: array of output error
        h0: array of inputs
        h1: array of hidden layer post-activations
        h2: array of hidden layer post-activations
        h3: array of hidden layer post-activations
    
    Returns:
        tuple of arrays of gradients
    """
    # calculate gradients by using formula in Step 5 
    grad_W0 = delta1[:, np.newaxis, :] * h0[:, :, np.newaxis]
    grad_b0 = delta1
    grad_W1 = delta2[:, np.newaxis, :] * h1[:, :, np.newaxis]
    grad_b1 = delta2
    grad_W2 = delta3[:, np.newaxis, :] * h2[:, :, np.newaxis]
    grad_b2 = delta3
    grad_W3 = delta4[:, np.newaxis, :] * h3[:, :, np.newaxis]
    grad_b3 = delta4
    
    # take average gradient over batchsize
    grad_W0 = np.mean(grad_W0, axis=0)
    grad_b0 = np.mean(grad_b0, axis=0)
    grad_W1 = np.mean(grad_W1, axis=0)
    grad_b1 = np.mean(grad_b1, axis=0)
    grad_W2 = np.mean(grad_W2, axis=0)
    grad_b2 = np.mean(grad_b2, axis=0)
    grad_W3 = np.mean(grad_W3, axis=0)
    grad_b3 = np.mean(grad_b3, axis=0)

    return grad_W0, grad_b0, grad_W1, grad_b1, grad_W2, grad_b2, grad_W3, grad_b3

Finally we will need to calculate the accuracy of our model which we will do by comparing our one-hot encoded target variable and the digit correpsonding to the output with the highest probability.

In [16]:
def accuracy(x_test, y_test, W0, b0, W1, b1, W2, b2, W3, b3):
    y_pred = np.argmax(mlp(x_test, W0, b0, W1, b1, W2, b2, W3, b3), axis=1)
    return np.mean(y_pred == y_test)

We can finally have the necessary functions needed to compile the MLP model. We first initialise our weight matrices and bias vectors. Then we loop over through each epoch shuffling our batches and passing it through our forward pass. After each batch we compute the prediction error and backpropagate, finding the errors of each pre-activation layer respectively. Then we compute the gradient of the parameters and use the SGD algorithm to minimise the loss. Then we input the entire training set into our network with the updated parameters to obtain the loss and accuracy of our model.

In [17]:
def multiLayerPerceptron(x_train_batch, y_train_batch, epochs, learning_rate, num_input, num_neuron, num_ouput, prt=False):
    
    # initialise parameters
    W0, b0, W1, b1, W2, b2, W3, b3 = glorotInitalise(num_input, num_neuron, num_ouput)
    
    # empty list to store loss and accuracy of training data
    loss_train = []
    acc_train = []

    # empty list to store loss and accuracy of testing data
    loss_test = []
    acc_test = []
    
    # get length of batched data then shuffle batch
    num_batches = len(x_train_batch)
    idx = np.arange(num_batches)
    
    # loop over epochs
    for epoch in range(epochs):
        
        # shuffle batch each epoch 
        np.random.shuffle(idx)
        x_train_batch = np.array(x_train_batch, dtype=object)[idx]
        y_train_batch = np.array(y_train_batch, dtype=object)[idx]
        
        # loop over mini-batches of training data 
        for x_batch, y_batch in zip(x_train_batch, y_train_batch):
            
            # one-hot encode output data
            y_batch = one_hot(y_batch)

            # forward pass (3 hidden layers)
            a1 = dense(x_batch, W0, b0) # pre-activation
            h1 = softplus(a1) # post-activation
            a2 = dense(h1, W1, b1)
            h2 = softplus(a2)
            a3 = dense(h2, W2, b2)
            h3 = softplus(a3)
            a4 = dense(h3, W3, b3)
            y_hat = softmax(a4) # output activation returns probability distribution 
            
            # backward pass (backpropagation)
            delta4 = output_error(y_batch, y_hat) # output error
            delta3 = backpropagate(delta4, W3, a3) # hidden layer error
            delta2 = backpropagate(delta3, W2, a2)
            delta1 = backpropagate(delta2, W1, a1)

            var_grads = grads(delta1, delta2, delta3, delta4, x_batch, h1, h2, h3)

            # stochastic gradient descent (SGD) update
            W0 = W0 - learning_rate * var_grads[0].T
            b0 = b0 - learning_rate * var_grads[1].T   
            W1 = W1 - learning_rate * var_grads[2].T
            b1 = b1 - learning_rate * var_grads[3].T
            W2 = W2 - learning_rate * var_grads[4].T
            b2 = b2 - learning_rate * var_grads[5].T
            W3 = W3 - learning_rate * var_grads[6].T
            b3 = b3 - learning_rate * var_grads[7].T

        # store loss and accuracy of entire train and test 
        l_train = np.mean(kl_loss(one_hot(y_train), mlp(x_train, W0, b0, W1, b1, W2, b2, W3, b3)))
        l_test = np.mean(kl_loss(one_hot(y_test), mlp(x_test, W0, b0, W1, b1, W2, b2, W3, b3)))
        
        a_train = accuracy(x_train, y_train, W0, b0, W1, b1, W2, b2, W3, b3)
        a_test = accuracy(x_test, y_test, W0, b0, W1, b1, W2, b2, W3, b3)
        
        # print out performance after each epoch to track progress
        if prt == True:
            print(f"Epoch {epoch+1} \n Training loss: {l_train}, Test loss: {l_test}, Training accuracy: {a_train}, Test accuracy: {a_test}")

        # append loss 
        loss_train.append(l_train)
        loss_test.append(l_test)

        # append accuracy
        acc_train.append(a_train)
        acc_test.append(a_test)

    return loss_train, loss_test, acc_train, acc_test, W0, b0

Using the training set we can train our MLP on batches of 128 data points for 40 epochs over learning rates varying from $10^{-5}$ to $10^{-1}$. We will then record the final loss achieved for each learning rate and plot it as a function of the learning rate.

Let us visualise the final loss against the learning rate.

In [19]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
plt.plot(learning_rates, final_loss, 'o-')
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xlabel('Learning rate')
plt.ylabel('Final loss')
plt.title('Final loss vs learning rate')
plt.show()

Overall we see that as the learning rate increases the final loss of the MLP on the training set decreases. We note a steep decrease between learning rates $10^{-3}$ and $10^{-2}$. However, we will set our learning rate to be $10^{-1}$.

1.1.2¶

1.1.4¶

Next we will modify our original model by including a dropout at each hidden layer, scaling the output of each neuron in the hidden layer to compensate for the dropout. Dropout is a regularisation technique for neural networks which randomly set connections between weights to 0 (zero out neurons) according to a Bernoulli distribution. One of the main reasons for dropout is that it reduces the behaviour of neurons co-adapting therefore neurons begin to learn features that a more robust and therefore reducing overfitting. In our model we will apply dropout during the training phase and when making predictions all weight connections will be restored and appropiately rescaled. We will utilise inverted dropout and will rescale in the backpropagation pass.

In [24]:
def multiLayerPerceptronDropout(x_train_batch, y_train_batch, epochs, learning_rate, num_input, num_neuron, num_ouput, p, prt=False):

    # initialise weight and bias
    W0, b0, W1, b1, W2, b2, W3, b3 = glorotInitalise(num_input, num_neuron, num_ouput)
    
    # lists to store loss and accuracy of training
    loss_train = []
    acc_train = []
    
    # lists to store loss and accuracy of testing 
    loss_test = []
    acc_test = []
    
    # number of batches in training data 
    num_batches = len(x_train_batch)
    idx = np.arange(num_batches)
    
    # loop for epochs
    for epoch in range(epochs):
        
        # shuffle the batches 
        np.random.shuffle(idx)
        x_train_batch = np.array(x_train_batch, dtype=object)[idx]
        y_train_batch = np.array(y_train_batch, dtype=object)[idx]
        
        # loop for batches
        for x_batch, y_batch in zip(x_train_batch, y_train_batch):
            
            # one hot encoding
            y_batch = one_hot(y_batch)

            # forward pass (3 hidden layers) with dropout 
            a1 = dense(x_batch, W0, b0)
            h1 = softplus(a1)
            U1 = np.random.binomial(1, 1-p, size=h1.shape) / (1-p) # first dropout mask
            h1 = h1 * U1
            a2 = dense(h1, W1, b1)
            h2 = softplus(a2)
            U2 = np.random.binomial(1, 1-p, size=h2.shape) / (1-p)
            h2 = h2 * U2
            a3 = dense(h2, W2, b2)
            h3 = softplus(a3)
            U3 = np.random.binomial(1, 1-p, size=h3.shape) / (1-p)
            h3 = h3 * U3
            a4 = dense(h3, W3, b3)
            y_hat = softmax(a4)
            
            # backpropagation with rescaling
            delta4 = output_error(y_batch, y_hat)
            delta3 = backpropagate(delta4, W3, a3) 
            delta3 = delta3 * U3 # rescale back
            delta2 = backpropagate(delta3, W2, a2)
            delta2 = delta2 * U2
            delta1 = backpropagate(delta2, W1, a1) 
            delta1 = delta1 * U1
            
            # calculate gradients
            var_grads = grads(delta1, delta2, delta3, delta4, x_batch, h1, h2, h3)

            # sgd update
            W0 = W0 - learning_rate * var_grads[0].T
            b0 = b0 - learning_rate * var_grads[1].T   
            W1 = W1 - learning_rate * var_grads[2].T
            b1 = b1 - learning_rate * var_grads[3].T
            W2 = W2 - learning_rate * var_grads[4].T
            b2 = b2 - learning_rate * var_grads[5].T
            W3 = W3 - learning_rate * var_grads[6].T
            b3 = b3 - learning_rate * var_grads[7].T
        
        # store loss and accuracy of entire train and test
        l_train = np.mean(kl_loss(one_hot(y_train), mlp(x_train, W0, b0, W1, b1, W2, b2, W3, b3)))
        l_test = np.mean(kl_loss(one_hot(y_test), mlp(x_test, W0, b0, W1, b1, W2, b2, W3, b3)))
        
        a_train = accuracy(x_train, y_train, W0, b0, W1, b1, W2, b2, W3, b3)
        a_test = accuracy(x_test, y_test, W0, b0, W1, b1, W2, b2, W3, b3)
        
        # print out performance after each epoch to track progress
        if prt:
            print(f"Epoch {epoch+1} \n Training loss: {l_train}, Test loss: {l_test}, Training accuracy: {a_train}, Test accuracy: {a_test}")

        # calculate loss 
        loss_train.append(l_train)
        loss_test.append(l_test)

        # calculate accuracy
        acc_train.append(a_train)
        acc_test.append(a_test)

    return loss_train, loss_test, acc_train, acc_test, W0, b0

1.2 Dimensionality reduction (20 marks)¶

In this task we will use Principal Component Analysis (PCA) and Negative Matrix Factorisation (NMF) to denoise images from a version of the MNIST dataset corrupted by zero mean Gaussian noise.

1.2.1¶

To start we will use PCA to carry out dimensionality reduction to denoise our images. PCA is a technique used to reduce the dimension and complexity of large datasets by transforming the data to a lower dimensional space. PCA works by computing the principal components of our data which are the directions of the data which explain the most variance. For our task we will reduce the dimension of our dataset using PCA then reconstruct the original images with some of the original information lost. To perform PCA on our dataset $X$ for $k$ principal components we will have to:

  1. Compute covariance matrix $C = X^T X / (n-1)$
  2. Compute eigenvalues and eigenvectors of the covariance matrix $C = VLV^T$
  3. Sort eigenvalues in descending order with corresponding eigenvectors
  4. Compute projection into space spanned by first $k$ eigenvectors.

Let us implement this procedure below in pca_function.

In [29]:
def pca_function(X,k):
    """
    Perform PCA on the data X, reducing the dimensionality to k dimensions

    Args:
        X: data matrix 
        k: number of principal components 
    
    Returns:
        X_pca: projected data matrix
        eigenvectors: eigenvectors of the covariance matrix
        eigenvalues: eigenvalues of the covariance matrix
    """

    # create covariance matrix S
    C = 1.0/(len(X)-1) * np.dot(X.T, X)

    # compute eigenvalues and eigenvectors using the eigsh scipy function
    eigenvalues, eigenvectors = linalg.eigsh(C, k, which="LM", return_eigenvectors=True) 

    # sorting the eigenvectors and eigenvalues from largest to smallest eigenvalue
    sorted_index = np.argsort(eigenvalues)[::-1]
    eigenvalues=eigenvalues[sorted_index]
    eigenvectors=eigenvectors[:,sorted_index ]

    # transform our data by projection onto the eigenvectors
    X_pca = X.dot(eigenvectors)

    return X_pca, eigenvectors, eigenvalues

Now we have a created a function to carry out PCA for us let investigate the fraction of variance explained by PCA for a range of $m$ principal components. The eigenvalues of the covariance matrix tell us the variance along each principal component. Therefore we will find the total variance by summing all the eigenvalues then calculate the fraction of variance by summing the first $m$ components. We will note the number of principal components that explain 70%, 80% and 90% of the variance.

1.2.2¶

Next we will use NMF to carry out dimensionality reduction for $m=10$ dimensions onto which we will projcet the data. NMF is a matrix factorisation technique where we constrain our matrices to be non-negative, unlike PCA where our factors could be both positive and neagtive. NMF factors our data matrix $X$ into non-negative factors $W$ and $H$, however, the factorisation is not exact and is rather an approximation. That is we have $X \approx WH$ where our factors $W$ and $H$ minimise the root mean square residual between $X$ and $WH$. To compute $W$ and $H$ we will use Lee and Seung's multiplicative update rule:

$$ \mathbf{H}_{[i,j]}^{n+1}\leftarrow \mathbf{H}_{[i,j]}^{n} \frac{(( \mathbf{W}^n)^T \mathbf{X})_{[i,j]}}{((\mathbf{W}^n)^T \mathbf{W}^n \mathbf{H}^n)_{[i,j]}} $$$$ \mathbf{W}_{[i,j]}^{n+1}\leftarrow \mathbf{W}_{[i,j]}^{n} \frac{(\mathbf{X}(\mathbf{H}^{n+1})^T)_{[i,j]}}{(\mathbf{W}^n \mathbf{H}^{n+1} (\mathbf{H}^{n+1})^T)_{[i,j]}}, $$

which we run until our factors are stable. This optimisation routine requires us to initialise our matrices and to have a cost function. Our cost function will be the root mean square residuals between our original matrix $X$ and the product of our factors $WH$. We will define our $\chi ^2$ as,

$$ \chi^2 = \frac{e^ \left(X \odot d \odot d \right) e}{n}, $$

where $d = X - WH$, $e$ is a vector of all ones and $n$ is the total number of elements in $X$, we also define $\odot$ to be the Hadamard product. Let us now create a cost function to compute our cost.

In [32]:
def cost(X,W,H):
    """
    Compute the cost function for the NMF algorithm

    Args:
        X: data matrix
        W: factor matrix
        H: factor matrix
    
    Returns:
        chi2: cost function
    """
  
    # compute the difference between X and the dot product of W and H
    diff = X - np.dot(W, H)

    chi2 = ((X*diff) * diff).sum() / (X.shape[0]*X.shape[1]) 
    
    return chi2

Now we have implemented our cost function let us implement the nmf algorithm and we will randomly initialise our factor matrices in the function.

In [33]:
def nmf(X, m, n_iters=200):
    """
    Perform NMF on the data X, reducing the dimensionality to m dimensions

    Args:
        X: data matrix
        m: number of components
        n_iters: number of iterations
    
    Returns:
        W: factor matrix
        H: factor matrix
        chi2: cost function
    """

    # set the seed for reproducibility
    np.random.seed(0)

    # m x k components matrix, usually interpreted as the coefficients, where m is the number of data
    W = np.random.rand(X.shape[0], m)

    # k x n matrix interpreted as the basis set, where n is the number of features (e.g. pixels)
    H = np.random.rand(m, X.shape[1])

    chi2 = []

    # loop over the n iterations
    for i in range(n_iters):

        # compute the update on H
        H = H * ((W.T.dot(X)) / W.T.dot(W.dot(H))) 

        # compute the update on W
        W = W * ((X.dot(H.T)) / (W.dot(H.dot(H.T))))

        # compute the chi2 and append to list
        chi2.append(cost(X,W,H))

    return W, H, chi2

Now we have implemented our NMF algorithm let us run it on $m=10$ dimensions and plot our loss function to ensure our number of iterations is sufficient for convergence.

We see that our components obtained from PCA and NMF differ this is due to the assumptions both procedures assume. In PCA it is assumes that the data can be represented as a linear combination of orthogonal components whereas NMF assumes the data can be represented as a linear combination of non-negative components. In PCA the aim is to explain the maximal variance of components but NMF identifies the most meaningful parts of the data; therefore different components would be identified. In PCA we are given components oriented to explain the maximum variance and therefore harder to interpret due to the addition of noise whereas NMF would produce components that are more interpretable but not capture the overall variance well. Additionally, PCA is perhaps more sensitive to noise due to computations from the covariance matrix but the NMF is more robust to noise due to the constraints on non-negative factors leading to sparser, more robust representations.

Now that we have trained our models let us turn our attention to the MNIST_test_noisy.txt dataset. First let us use PCA to reconstruct our image. For PCA we have that,

$$ \mathbf{X}_{\text{train}} \approx (\mathbf{X}_{\text{projection matrix}} \cdot \text{eigenvector} \cdot \text{eigenvector}^T) \cdot \sigma_{\text{train}} + \mu_{\text{train}}, $$

where the projection matrix is of the image we wish to reconstruct, the eigenvectors of our covariance matrix and mean are from the training dataset. Now we have a formula let us implement our PCA reconstruction.

In [38]:
def reconstruction_pca(train, test, m, train_mean, train_std):
    """
    Image reconstruction using PCA
    
    Args:
        train: array of training data assumed to be standardised
        test: array of testing data assumed to be standardised
        m: number of components to use
        train_mean: mean of training data
        train_std: standard deviation of training data
        
    Returns:
        array of reconstructed images
    """
    # compute PCA matrix, eigenvectors and eigenvalues of training data
    pca, evector, evalue = pca_function(train, m)
    
    # apply formula to compute reconstruction
    X_reconstructed = ((test @ evector) @ evector.T) * train_std
    return X_reconstructed + train_mean

Now let us turn our attention to NMF, we have that the reconstructed image is a linear combination of the non-negative components. To do so, we will train our NMF on the training data to compute $\mathbf{H}$ our non-negative components. Next we will compute $\mathbf{W}$ by randomly initialising and then running the multiplicative update rule to compute coefficients this is done to create orthogonal components. Thus we have the formula,

$$ \mathbf{X}_{\text{test}} \approx \mathbf{W} \mathbf{H}_{\text{train}}, $$

then we undo the normalisation step to obtain our denoised test image. With this formulation let us implement below.

In [40]:
def reconstruction_nmf(train, test, m):
    """
    Image reconstruction using NMF
    
    Args:
        train: array of training data
        test: array of testing data
        m: number of non-negative components
        
    Returns:
        array of reconstructed images
    """
    # obtain non-negative components of training data 
    _, H, _ = nmf(train, m)
    
    # randomly initialise coefficients
    W = np.random.rand(test.shape[0], m)
    # loop to update coefficients
    for i in range(200):
        W = W * np.dot(test, H.T)/np.dot(np.dot(W, H), H.T) 
    
    # multiple coefficients and components then undo normalisation
    X_reconstructed = (W @ H) * (np.max(test) - np.min(test)) + np.min(test)
    return X_reconstructed

1.3 Gaussian Mixture Models (20 marks)¶

We will now explore clustering using Gaussian Mixture Models (GMM). Mixture models are generative models used for clustering consisting of mixture components and weights such that the marginal distribution is a convex combination of the two. We will use GMM to approximate our data and in this case our mixture components follow are Gaussian distribution. We define our GMM as,

$$ P(\boldsymbol{X}=\boldsymbol{x}) = \sum_{k=1}^K \pi_k p_k(\boldsymbol{x}|\boldsymbol{\theta})\, . $$

where $K$ is the number of clusters described by mixture components. As mentioned, each mixture component follow multivariate Gaussian distributions, $$ p_k(\boldsymbol{x}|\boldsymbol{\theta}) = {\displaystyle (2\pi )^{-k/2}\det({\boldsymbol {\Sigma }_k})^{-1/2}\,\exp \left(-{\frac {1}{2}}(\mathbf {x} -{\boldsymbol {\mu }_k})^{\!{\mathsf {T}}}{\boldsymbol {\Sigma }_k}^{-1}(\mathbf {x} -{\boldsymbol {\mu }_k})\right),} $$ where $\boldsymbol{\theta} = \{\pi_k,\mu_k, \Sigma_k \}_{k=1,2,...,K}$ is the vectors of parameters consiting of the mixture weight $\pi_k$, mixture component mean $\boldsymbol{\mu}_k$ and mixture component covariance matrix $\boldsymbol{\mu}_k$.

1.3.1¶

We will use the first 5 principal components of the PCA on the first 1000 images from MNIST_train.csv to perform clustering use a Gaussian Mixture Model with 10 hidden components. First let us obtain our required matrix below then create a GMmodel class.

In [48]:
X131_pca, eigenvectors_131, eigenvalues_131 = pca_function(x_train_pca[:1000, :], 5)
In [49]:
class GMModel:
    """Struct to define the Gas=ussian Mixture Model"""
    """:param dim: number of mixture components"""
    """:param weights: mixture weights"""
    """:param mu: mixture component means for each cluster"""
    """param sigma: mixture component covariance matrix for each cluster"""

    def __init__(self, X, dim):
        """Initialises parameters through random split of the data"""

        self.dim = dim

        """ inital weights given to each cluster are stored in phi or P(Ci=j)"""
        self.phi = np.full(shape=self.dim, fill_value=1/self.dim)
        
        """ initial weights given to each data point wrt to each cluster of P(Xi/Ci=j)"""
        self.weights = np.full(shape=X.shape, fill_value=1/self.dim)

        n, m = X.shape
        # dataset is divided randomly into k parts of unequal sizes
        random_row = np.random.randint(low=0, high=n, size=self.dim)

        # initial value of mean of k Gaussians
        self.mu = [X[row_index,:] for row_index in random_row]

        # initial value of covariance matrix of k Gaussians
        self.sigma = [np.cov(X.T) for _ in range(self.dim)]

In GMM we perform soft clustering as oppose to hard clustering using the clustering probability,

$$r_{ik}(\boldsymbol{\theta})=P(Z=k|\boldsymbol{X}=\boldsymbol{x}_i,\boldsymbol{\theta}) = \frac{\pi_k p_k(\boldsymbol{x}_i|\boldsymbol{\theta})}{\sum_{k'=1}^K \pi_{k'} p_{k'}(\boldsymbol{x}_i|\boldsymbol{\theta})},$$

which produces a distribution for each data point as it denotes the probability of data $i$ belonging to cluster $k$. Let's implement this below.

In [50]:
def cluster_probabilities(gmm, X):
    """
    Predicts probability of each data point with respect to each cluster
    
    Args: 
        gmm: Gaussian Mixture Model
        X: dataset
    
    Returns:
        weights: probability of each data point with respect to each cluster
    """
    
    # n has the number of rows while m has the number of columns of dataset X
    n, m = X.shape
    # Creates a n*k matrix denoting likelihood belonging to each cluster 
    likelihood = np.zeros((n, gmm.dim))
    for i in range(gmm.dim):
        # likelihood of data belonging to i-th cluster 
        distribution = multivariate_normal(mean=gmm.mu[i], cov=gmm.sigma[i])
        likelihood[:,i] = distribution.pdf(X)

        # weights of data belonging to i-th cluster
        numerator = likelihood * gmm.phi
        denominator = numerator.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        weights = numerator / denominator

    return weights

However, we wish to convert the soft clustering to hard clustering by taking the argmax of the distribution, this is for visualisation puroposes.

In [51]:
def predict(gmm, X):
    """
    Performs hard clustering

    Args:
        gmm: Gaussian Mixture Model
        X: dataset
    
    Returns:
        cluster: cluster to which each data point belongs
    """
    weights = cluster_probabilities(gmm, X)
    return np.argmax(weights, axis=1)

def draw_ellipse(position, covariance, ax=None, **kwargs):
    """Draw an ellipse with a given position and covariance"""
    ax = ax or plt.gca()
    
    # Convert covariance to principal axes
    if covariance.shape == (2, 2):
        U, s, Vt = np.linalg.svd(covariance)
        angle = np.degrees(np.arctan2(U[1, 0], U[0, 0]))
        width, height = 2 * np.sqrt(s)
    else:
        angle = 0
        width, height = 2 * np.sqrt(covariance)
    
    # Draw the Ellipse
    for nsig in range(1, 4):
        ax.add_patch(Ellipse(position, nsig * width, nsig * height,
                             angle, **kwargs))
    
def plot_gmm(gmm, X, label=True, ax=None):
    ax = ax or plt.gca()
    labels = predict(gmm,X)
    if label:
        ax.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=labels, s=40, cmap='viridis', zorder=2)
    else:
        ax.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], s=40, zorder=2)
    ax.axis('equal')
    
    return ax

We can turn our attention to fitting the data, which we will us the EM algorithm to do so. The aim of the EM algorithm is to improve the marginal likelihood of the data by replacing the empirical averages with weighted averages corresponding to cluster probabilities. We begin by updating the mixture weights,

$$ \pi_k^{(n+1)} = \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^N r_{ik}(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{(n)}). $$

Then using the weighted means we compute the cluster means, then update the covariances,

$$ \boldsymbol{\mu}_k^{(n+1)} =\sum_{i=1}^N w_{ik}(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{(n)}) \boldsymbol{x}_i, $$$$\boldsymbol{\Sigma}_k^{(n+1)}= \sum_{i=1}^N w_{ik}(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{(n)}) (\boldsymbol{x}_i-\boldsymbol{\mu}_k) (\boldsymbol{x}_i-\boldsymbol{\mu}_k)^T.$$

We can then compute the weights from the cluster probabilities through,

$$w_{ik}(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{(n)})=\frac{r_{ik}(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{(n)})}{\sum_{i'} r_{i'k}(\boldsymbol{\theta}^{(n)})}$$

We will implement fitStep which will perform one iteration of the EM algorithm

In [53]:
def fitStep(gmm, X):
    """
    Performs an EM step by updating all parameters

    Args:
        gmm: Gaussian Mixture Model
        X: dataset

    Returns:
        gmm: Gaussian Mixture Model
    """

    weights = cluster_probabilities(gmm, X)
    gmm.phi = weights.mean(axis=0)

    for i in range(gmm.dim):
        weight = weights[:, [i]]
        total_weight = weight.sum()

        gmm.mu[i] = (X * weight).sum(axis=0) / total_weight
        gmm.sigma[i] = np.cov(X.T, aweights = (weight/total_weight).flatten(), bias=True)

2.1 Clustering (15 marks)¶

Given our 800 x 95 matrix of gene expression levels we will implement $k$-means on these datas to find groups of samples with similar gene expression patterns.

$k$-means is an algorithm in unsuperivised learning where we aim to group $N$ samples into $k$ clusters where each sample is assigned to a cluster whose centroid is closest to, an iterative scheme which updates the centroids until convergence.

We will run $k$-means over a range of values of $k$ to find the optimal number of clusters using the average Calinski-Harabasz index over 5 initialisation for each $k$ as our score.

2.1.1¶

Before we implement $k$-means let us define our Calinksi-Harabasz index. The Calinksi-Harabasz index measures the clustering quality as a ratio of the between-cluster scatter matrix and within-cluster scatter matrix. It is defined as

$$ \text{CH}_k = \frac{\text{BCSM}}{k-1} \cdot \frac{n-k}{\text{WCSM}}, $$

where BCSM is based on the distances between clusters,

$$ \text{BCSM} = \sum_{i=1}^k n_i \cdot d(z_i, z_{\text{tot}})^2, $$

and WCSM is based on the distances within clusters,

$$ \text{WCSM} = \sum_{i=1}^{k} \sum_{x \in c_i} d(x, z_i)^2, $$

where $n$ is the total number of points, $k$ is the number of clusters, $z_i$ is the center of cluster $c_i$, $n_i$ is the number of points in $c_i$ and $d(x,y)$ is the Euclidean distance.

In [70]:
def calinskiHarabaszIndex(X, labels, centroids, k):
    """
    Compute the Calinski-Harabasz index for a given number of clusters

    Args:
        X: array of data points
        labels: array of cluster labels
        centroids: array of cluster centroids
        k: number of clusters
    
    Returns:
        Calinski-Harabasz index for the given number of clusters
    """

    # compute BCSM 
    bcsm = np.sum([len(X[labels == i]) * np.sum((centroids[i] - np.mean(X, axis = 0)) ** 2) for i in range(k)])

    # compute WCSSM
    wcsm = np.sum([np.sum((X[labels == i] - centroids[i]) ** 2) for i in range(k)])

    # compute Calinksi-Harabasz index
    return ((bcsm * (len(X) - k))) / ((k - 1) * (wcsm))

Now we have created a function that computes the Calinksi-Harabasz index we can implement $k$-means with our score function.

In [71]:
def k_means(X, k, max_iter=30, prt=False):
    """
    Perform k-means clustering on a given dataset

    Args:
        X: array of data 
        k: number of clusters
        max_iter: maximum number of iterations
        prt: print the number of iterations
    
    Returns:
        labels: array of cluster labels
        centroids: array of cluster centroids
    """
    
    n_samples, n_features = X.shape
    
    new_labels = np.zeros(len(X))
    difference = 0

    # labels: assign every sample to a cluster at random
    labels = np.random.randint(low=0, high=k, size=n_samples)
    X_labels = np.append(X, labels.reshape(-1,1), axis=1)

    # computing the centroids of each of the k clusters
    centroids = np.zeros((k, n_features))
    for i in range(k):
        # if no samples assigned to a cluster then assign centroid to mean of all samples
        if (labels == i).any() == False:
            centroids[i] = np.mean(X, axis=0)[0:n_features]
        else:
            centroids[i] = np.mean([x for x in X_labels if x[-1]==i], axis=0)[0:n_features]

    # k-means algorithm
    for i in range(max_iter):
        if prt == True:
            print('Iteration:', i)
        # distances: between data points and centroids
        distances = np.array([np.linalg.norm(X - c, axis=1) for c in centroids])
        # new_labels: computed by finding centroid with minimal distance
        new_labels = np.argmin(distances, axis=0)

        if (labels==new_labels).all():
            # labels unchanged
            labels = new_labels
            if prt == True:
                print('Labels unchanged! Terminating k-means.')
            break
        else:
            # labels changed
            # difference: percentage of changed labels
            difference = np.mean(labels!=new_labels)    
            if prt == True:
                print('%4f%% labels changed' % (difference * 100))
            labels = new_labels
            for c in range(k):
                # update centroids by taking the mean over associated data points
                if (labels == c).any():
                    centroids[c] = np.mean(X[labels==c], axis=0)   
                    
    return centroids, labels

2.1.2¶

Now we have obtained our optimal $k$ we would like to evaluate the consistency between our clustering obtained through $k$-means and the assigned classes. To do so we will compute the homogeneity score which measures the extent to which the data points in one cluster belong to the same class. The homogeneity score given a set of classes $C$ and clusters $K$ is given by,

$$ \text{Homogeneity Score} = 1 - \frac{H(C|K)}{H(C)}. $$

We define the conditional entropy $H(C|K$ as, $$ H(C|K) = - \sum_{k=1}^{|K|} \sum_{c=1}^{|C|} \frac{a_{ck}}{N} \log\left(\frac{a_{ck}}{\sum_{c=1}^{|C|} a_{ck}} \right), $$ and the entropy $H(C)$ as, $$ H(C) = - \sum_{c=1}^{|C|} \frac{\sum_{k=1}^{|K|} a_{ck}}{N} \log \left( \frac{\sum_{k=1}^{|K|} a_{ck}}{N} \right), $$ where $|C|$ and $|K|$ are the sizes of $C, K$, $N$ is the total number of data points, $a_{ck}$ is the number of data points in class $c$ and assigned to cluster $k$.

Before we implement a function to compute the homogeneity score we will obtain the correct class label for each data point and assign a numeric value for each tumour type.

def homogeneityScore(y_true, y_pred):
    """
    Compute the homogeneity score for a given clustering

    Args:
        y_true: array of true labels
        y_pred: array of predicted labels
    
    Returns:
        homogeneity score for the given clustering
    """

    # empty array to store counts of each class in each cluster
    a = np.zeros((len(np.unique(y_true)), len(np.unique(y_pred))))

    # for loop to count the number of samples in each cluster for each class
    for i in range(len(y_true)):
        a[y_true[i]][y_pred[i]] += 1
    
    # sum over rows and columns to get the number of samples in each class and cluster
    class_count = np.sum(a, axis=1)
    cluster_count = np.sum(a, axis=0)

    # compute conditional entropy 
    conditional_entropy = 0
    for k in range(len(np.unique(y_pred))):
        for c in range(len(np.unique(y_true))):
            # if no samples in a cluster then skip
            if a[c][k] != 0:
                conditional_entropy += a[c][k]/len(y_true) * np.log((a[c][k] + 1e-20)/cluster_count[k])

    # compute entropy
    entropy = 0
    for c in range(len(np.unique(y_true))):
        entropy += np.sum(class_count[c])/len(y_true) * np.log(np.sum(class_count[c])/len(y_true)) 

    homogeneity = 1 - conditional_entropy/entropy

    return homogeneity

Now we have our function to compute the homogeneity score let us compute the homogeneity score for our optimal $k$.

2.2.4¶

Let us define a 95 x 18 matrix $U$ containing the 18 eigenvectors of the symmetric normalised Laplacian corresponding to 0 eigenvalues as columns. Then we will create a new matrix $T$ of size 95 x 18 by normalising the rows of $U$ to 1,

$$ T_{ij} = \frac{U_{ij}}{\sqrt {\sum_{k}U_{ik}^2}}. $$
In [82]:
U = eigenvectors[:,:18]
T = U/(np.sqrt(np.sum(U**2, axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]))

Using our normalised matrix T we will apply $k$-means to the matrix over a range of $k$. We will use the normalised within-cluster distance and the elbow method to set the appropiate value of $k$. The within-cluster distance is defined as

$$ W(C) = \frac{1}{2} \sum_{l=1}^{k} \frac{1}{|c_l|} \sum_{i, \ j \in c_l} ||X^{(i)} - X^{(j)}||^2 = \sum_{l=1}^{k} \sum_{i \in c_l} ||X^{(i)} - \textbf{m}_l||^2 $$

which measures the distances between points in a given cluster.

In [83]:
def within_cluster_distance(X, k):
    """
    Compute the within-cluster distance for a given clustering

    Args:
        X: data matrix
        k: number of clusters
    
    Returns:
        within-cluster distance for the given clustering
    """
    # compute the centroids and labels for the given clustering
    centroid, label = k_means(X, k)
    # compute the within-cluster distance
    W = 0
    for l in range(k):
        W += np.sum(np.linalg.norm(X[label==l] - centroid[l])**2) # sum of 2-norms
    return W

2.2.5¶

Considering the biggest cluster identified in $\mathbf{2.2.4}$ let us re-calculate the normalised Laplacian of the cluster and the corresponding eigenvalues and eigenvectors.

In [87]:
# compute the adjacency matrix of the largest cluster
A_225 = A[labels_224 == big_clust][:, labels_224 == big_clust]
degree_centrality_225 = np.sum(A_225, axis=0)/np.sum(A_225)

# dictionary to track genes from original adjacency matrix to corresponding new adjacency matrix
A_225_idx_original = {}
for i in range(clust[big_clust]):
    A_225_idx_original[i] = np.where(labels_224 == big_clust)[0][i]

# compute symmetric normalised Laplacian
degree_225 = np.sum(A_225, axis=0)
weighted_degree_sqrt_225 = 1.0/np.sqrt(degree_225)
D_inv_sqrt_225 = np.diag(weighted_degree_sqrt_225)
L_norm_225 = np.eye(A_225.shape[0]) - D_inv_sqrt_225.dot(A_225.dot(D_inv_sqrt_225))

# compute the second smallest eigenvalue and eigenvector of the symmetric normalised Laplacian
eigenvals_225, eigenvecs_225 = linalg.eigsh(L_norm_225, 2, which="SM", return_eigenvectors=True)

second_eigenvec_225 = eigenvecs_225[:,1]

Using the second eigenvalue (spectral gap) we will use the corresponding eigenvector (Fiedler vector) to perform spectral clustering. We will set negative values to 0 and positive values to 1. This will results in a binary partition of the subgraph. Then we will use histograms to visualise the magnitude of the network links within each partition and across the 2 partitions.

In [88]:
# partition the nodes into 2 clusters based on the sign of the second eigenvector
spectral_partition = second_eigenvec_225
spectral_partition[spectral_partition < 0] = 0
spectral_partition[spectral_partition > 0] = 1

# compute the adjacency matrices of the two clusters
idx0 = np.where(spectral_partition == 0)
idx1 = np.where(spectral_partition == 1)

# np.squeeze to remove extra dimension
A_225_0 = np.squeeze(A_225[idx0][:, idx0])
A_225_1 = np.squeeze(A_225[idx1][:, idx1])
